Mercedes-Benz GLA review
The Mercedes-Benz GLA is another contender in the increasingly impressive class of small SUVs
4
The Mercedes-Benz GLA is based on the A-class hatchback By Andrew English
3:00PM GMT 25 Feb 2014
Comments
Two years before the arrival of this new GLA, Mercedes-Benz launched the latest A-class with the line “A for attack”. It’s a premium manufacturer’s conceit to think it can do anything better than a non-premium counterpart, but in Mercedes’s case it has made a pretty good fist of building a Focus-sized series of models. This latest version is the GLA SUV, the fourth A-class derivative after the A- and B-class and CLA, all using the same basic chassis and front-wheel drive greasy bits. They’ve been doing bonanza business for Mercedes. Unexpectedly so, admitted Zetsche at Detroit in January, when he said that in addition to A-class production in Germany and eastern Europe he was also looking at making the cars in Finland. Since last year, the UK has bought 18,000 A-class models, with 70 per cent of buyers new to the three-pointed star. The GLA soft-roader should be just as successful, especially since it sells into one of the fastest growing markets in the world. Mercedes calls the GLA’s design “sensual purity” – I laughed, too. It’s wedgy and pretty anodyne but, like the rest of the A-class family, slippery through the air, with a drag coefficient of 0.29. Aerodynamics manager Norbert Fecker explained how beneficial this can be. Related Articles
