BMW X1 x drive 28i review
15 Apr 2011
“If you were doing say 70mph,” he said, “and the engine was consuming fuel at the rate of 53.3mpg and then you increased the aerodynamic drag by 0.01, your consumption would increase to 44.84mpg and the equivalent weight increase in the car would be 175kg [385lb].” So now you know. Like a lot of compact SUVs, it’s hard to see the corners of the GLA from behind the wheel, so it’s just as well the reversing camera is standard. And it’s not just the body that’s low in this car (it’s 2.5in lower than a Nissan Qashqai, 1.7in lower than a BMW X1), but you sit low as well. Just 1.5in higher than in an A-class and subjectively not much higher than the general traffic. Which seems an odd decision, since whenever you see market feedback on the appeal of SUVs, the commanding (high) driving position is always cited, particularly by women. The cabin is spacious, airy and full of useful storage. All the seats are reasonably comfy and the sports items in the AMG version are very supportive (as they need to be). The cabin’s design echoes that of the A-class so the instrument binnacle, the porthole air vents on the facia, the central screen and clear sans serif graphics are the same. The door cards feel hollow and cheap, however, some of the press cars were bedecked with a spectacularly fake timber facia and in places there were mismatched trim panels. There’s a generous amount of space in the rear and the back of the seat can be tilted upright to increase the size of the boot to 481 litres, which is almost 40 per cent bigger than the standard A-class. The UK’s most popular version is likely to be the 220 CDI diesel with four-wheel drive and Merc’s seven-speed, semi-automatic, twin-clutch transmission. Actually the 200 CDI version of the same engine is more refined and quieter, but also pretty slow, especially if you chose the all-wheel-drive, automatic version. The extra power and torque of the 220 CDI gives welcome get up and go to this 1.55-ton car (134mph, 8.3sec, 57.6mpg and 129g/km of CO2) and the automatic changes up briskly and early, which mitigates high-rev harshness. In comparison, the 2.0-litre turbocharged petrol unit in the 250 is nicely refined (143mph, 7.1mpg, 42.8mpg and 154g/km), but its extra thirst means it won’t be as popular. The GLA 45 AMG is an extraordinary device. Its unfeasibly quick 355bhp four-cylinder, 2.0-litre has 355bhp and is boosted at more than 26psi, so much you fear the little engine will get the bends if you lift off the throttle sharply. It’s limited to 155mph, does 0-62mph in 4.8sec, delivers 37.6mpg and 175g/km. Quite what it is for is beyond us and, at a price north of £42,000, it’s competing against serious kit such as Porsche’s Macan and we’re not sure it’s good enough in that company. The standard A-class is far from being the finest riding vehicle in its class and on sports suspension it feels like a wheelie bin on a staircase. The GLA rides about 2in higher than a standard A-class and, as a result, has more wheel travel. The test cars were also shod with 235/50/R18 Yokohamas and had the standard “Comfort” suspension for the MacPherson strut front and multilink rear suspension. Consequently, they rode better, the suspension "breathed" better on undulations and didn’t crash into potholes. It’s far from perfect, but so much better than the A-class. Mercedes has improved the handling, too. Turn-in to bends is slightly slower and more deliberate and there’s more body roll, but there’s also a more faithful response to the steering. Understeer is there but it’s not excessive and the 4x4 system keeps the whole shebang roughly in the direction of travel even if you play the fool. The steering is inconsistent in the way it loads up, but it’s accurate and nicely weighted at shopping speeds. But is this really a sports utility vehicle? Most will be sold with four-wheel drive, there’s a standard hill-descent control and from later this year you can order an "Off-Road" pack including an off-road setting for the electronic stability control and suspension raised by just over an inch. We drove these vehicles on a small off-road course at the Spanish launch. Frankly you could have pushed a four-poster bed around it and even in "head for the boondocks" trim the GLA has about as much off-road ambition as a pair of bunny rabbit slippers. If the standard A-class had never happened and the GLA was introduced instead, no one would have batted an eyelid. The GLA is a fine driving machine, not horribly compromised, economical and not exorbitantly priced (for a Mercedes). Just don’t talk about SUVs, because it isn’t. THE FACTS Mercedes-Benz GLA 220 CDI 4Matic Tested: 2,143cc four-cyl turbodiesel, seven-speed semi-automatic, four-wheel drive Price/on sale: £30,030 as tested (range £25,850 to £31,030, AMG versions £42,000 to £45,000)/now Power/torque: 167bhp @ 3,400rpm/258lb ft @ 1,400rpm Top speed: 134mph Acceleration: 0-62mph in 8.3sec Fuel economy: 57.6mpg (EU Combined) CO2 emissions: 129g/km VED band: D (£0 first year, £105 thereafter) Verdict: Try to forget the SUV description and you are left with a fine-riding, economical and not unattractive five-door hatchback. Whether that’s enough to convince folk that there’s sufficient difference between this and an A-class remains to be seen Telegraph rating: Four out of five stars RIVALS Nissan Qashqai, from £17,595 Non-premium market leader, though you can spec up a Qashqai to near the entry-level price for the GLA. Much improved and larger cabin with a good ride and handling compromise. BMW X1, from £25,755 Not BMW’s finest hour, with an awkward looking body and choppy ride quality for this 3-series-based SUV. Cabin only just passes muster, although there’s a good range of drivelines. Range Rover Evoque, from £29,200 Land Rover’s baby has stolen hearts in this sector in spite of high prices and cramped rear seats. The cabin is classy, off-road ability is good and it goes well, but not brilliantly economical. Follow @TeleMotoring
