Mr Curlewis also pointed out that Tuesday's bail hearing would only concentrate on "whether to grant bail or not." "It's not a question of guilt or innocence at this stage of the proceedings. That is only to be determined in a couple of months' time from now." Pistorius made history at the London Games last year when he became the first double-amputee track athlete to compete in the Olympics. Known as 'the Blade Runner' a nickname that plays off the hi-tech carbon-fibre blades that he races on, Pistorius remains in custody in a red-bricked, one-storey police station in Pretoria. Reeva, a blonde-haired model, law graduate and reality TV contestant, died last week of multiple gunshot wounds suffered inside Pistorius' upscale home. A 9mm pistol was recovered from the scene and Pistorius was arrested and charged with murder the same day. Prosecutors said in Pistorius' first court appearance on Friday that they would pursue a more serious pre-mediated murder charge against the Olympian and world's most high-profile disabled athlete. His family strongly denies he committed murder. The bail hearing will be the first time the prosecutors and defence will show their hands about the evidence involved in the killing. Pistorius' lawyers will likely try to show that he is not a flight risk and represents no danger to the community if he is free until trial. Prosecutors have said they will pursue a premeditated murder charge against Pistorius, which could make it more difficult for him to be granted bail. South Africa is one of a few countries in the world that that has a court system that takes root in Roman-Dutch law. Because of this, those appearing in criminal trials do not have the option of a jury trial, common in the US and other countries. Instead, a single judge will hear the entire case and then rule on a person's guilt or innocence. A premeditated murder charge carries a minimum sentence of life in prison. There is no death penalty in South Africa. Contains video from 